nd national context, Lizbet Simmons shows how young black males are in the liminal state of losing educational affiliation while being caught in the net of correctional control. In The Prison School, she asks how schools and prisons became so intertwined. What does this mean for students, communities, and a democratic society? And how do we unravel the ties that bind the racialized realities of school failure and mass incarceration?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAfrican American young menxDisciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menxEducationxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menxEducationzLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menzLouisianazNew OrleansxDiscipline. 0aJuvenile correctionsxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aJuvenile correctionszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aSchool disciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aSchool disciplinezLouisianazNew Orleans. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aafrican american.  ablack boys.  ablack males.  ablack men.  ablack.  acorrectional control.  acriminal justice.  acriminology.  adisciplinary offenses.  adiscipline.  aeducation policy.  aeducation.  aexpulsion.  alouisiana.  amass incarceration.  anew orleans.  aorleans parish prison.  apenology.  apoverty.  aprison school.  aprobation.  apublic school.  apunishment.  arace.  aracism.  arecidivism.  aschool administration.  aschool dropout.  aschool to prison pipeline.  asocial issues.  asocial science.  asocioeconomic disparity.  asuspension.  aurban.  awar on crime.  ayouth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028145540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520293144423Coveruhttps://www